t the communities around Bagram Airbase, this ethnography considers how Afghans viewed and attempted to use the intervention and how those at the base tried to understand the communities around them. These compelling stories step outside the tired paradigms of 'unruly' Afghan tribes, an effective Taliban resistance, and a corrupt Karzai government to show how the intervention became an entity unto itself, one doomed to collapse under the weight of its own bureaucracy and contradictory intentions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfghan War, 2001-xPolitical aspects. 0aEconomic assistancezAfghanistan. 0aNation-buildingzAfghanistan. 4aAfghanistan. 4aBagram. 4aSEALs. 4aconflict. 4acontracting. 4acounterinsurgency. 4adevelopment. 4aethnography. 4aintervention. 4astate-building. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479780140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797801423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797801.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles